se:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"In what country, between the 1950s and 1980, would one have found \"\"Rusticated Youth\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho is the only US President who did not speak English as his first language?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn which sport is it forbidden for anyone to play left handed?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn WTF taekwondo competitions points are scored for a kick to the head or body, a turning kick to the head, and what else?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"What does the word \"\"fine\"\" mean on sheet music?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat country changed its name to Burkina Faso?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the opposite side from starboard on a ship?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"John Wayne appeared as a centurion in the film \"\"The Greatest Story Ever Told\"\" (1965). What was his famous line?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe Gunpowder Plot, by discontented Catholics including Guy Fawkes and Robert Catesby, was to blow up the British parliament as it was being opened by whom?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe islands called the Moluccas were previously known as what?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Who \"\"was born in a cross-fire hurricane\"\" and \"\"howled at my ma in the driving rain\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nA nectarine is a shiny-skinned variety of what?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"What kind of ship was the Japanese \"\"Hsh\"\", commissioned on 27 December 1922, the first purpose-designed ship of its kind to be commissioned anywhere in the world?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhen Sir Alex Ferguson retired in May 2013 after 26 years as manager for Manchester United Football Club who succeeded him ?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the name for a natural satellite that orbits a planet?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat system of psychology, popularised by F J Gall and J K Spurzheim in the 19th century, claims that mental faculties and dispositions can be determined by the shape of the skull?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the name of a calculating machine that originally consisted of beans or stones moved in grooves in sand or on tablets of wood, stone, or metal?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Which American country singer, the younger sister of singer Loretta Lynn, had 18 #1 country hits during the 1970s and 1980s, and is best known for a series of country-pop crossover hits including \"\"Don't It Make My Brown Eyes Blue\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhen was curling first played as a Winter Olympic sport?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIf a chess player completes a move known as en passant, what pieces are involved?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhere is the Australian parliament based?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"What English model, with her short-haired androgynous look, born Lesley Hornby, was discovered in 1966 by Nigel Davies when she was 16 and weighed 6 stone (41 kg, 91 lbs), and became \"\"The Face of '66\"\" with her high fashion mod look created by Mary Quant?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich British TV comedy series of the 1970s and early 1980s (74 episodes) was co-created and co-written by and co-starred Tim Brooke-Taylor, Graeme Garden and Bill Oddie?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat kind of bird is a guillemot?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat information technology company was founded by Sergey Brin and Larry Page?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nMuslin and chenille are two what?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhose alter ego is Sasha Fierce?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhere is the Arafura Sea?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"In 1858 Rowland Macy established a new store named \"\"R. H. Macy & Company\"\", where it stayed on the same site for nearly forty years, in which city?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe 2010 Six Nations Championship, the 11th series of an annual rugby union competition contested by the six major Northern Hemisphere rugby union national teams, was won by France. Which nation won it in 2009 and came second in 2010 and 2011?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is an alternative name for members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is a mosquito-borne virus, also known as breakbone fever, that is an acute febrile disease which occurs widely in the tropics, in Asia, South America, Australia and the Pacific and is now endemic in more than 100 countries?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich Spaniard, from 1518, overcame Montezuma, captured Mexico City and became Governor-General of much of Mexico?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn the northern hemisphere, what season begins in one calendar year and ends in the next?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nUntil the introduction of the euro, on 1 January 2002, which country had the schilling as its basic currency unit?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich cricketer captained England to a record 54 test matches in 2001?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is a Jacob's Ladder?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nChristmas Island is administered by which country?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich Christian festival is celebrated on 6 January, the 12th day after Christmas, to commemorate the coming of the Magi?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nLake Neuchatel is in which country?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhere is The Bridge of Sighs?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich fashionable London thoroughfare, about three quarters of a mile (1.2 km) long, runs from Hyde Park Corner to Marble Arch, along the length of the eastern side of Hyde Park?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is a commmon name for the United Nations peacekeeping forces?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nA holiday on 25 March in Greece celebrates the final recognition of Greece as an independent nation following the Greek War of Independence against the Ottoman Empire. What year did this happen?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nHow many odd numbers are there between 12 and 42?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nSir Basil Spence is associated with what activity?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho first identified and isolated nucleic acids, the precursor to identifying DNA?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho is the next in this series: John L. Sullivan, James J. Corbett, Bob Fitzsimmons, James J. Jeffries, Marvin Hart, ... ?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nA second referendum is due to be held for which commonwealth to decide whether, among other options, to become the 51st state of the USA?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn June 2009 American neuroscientist Dr Gary Arendash claimed to have evidence that drinking a few cups of coffee a day could prevent or reverse the effects of what?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat was the name of the operation whereby 1,373 U.S. citizens and 5,595 Vietnamese and foreign nationals were evacuated from the South Vietnamese capital of Saigon on 29 and 30 April 1975?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Who was \"\"the maid of Orleans\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe world's first publicly subscribed passenger railway, the Stockton and Darlington, opened in England with steam engines when?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"The words \"\"Polyalphaolefins\"\", \"\"dibasic acide esters\"\", \"\"dibasic acide diesters\"\", and \"\"polyol esters-based\"\" and \"\"diester-based\"\" are used in connection with the development of what?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhen was Uluru (Ayers Rock) in the Northern Territory of Australia declared a World Heritage Site?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich Soviet leader was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1990?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhere is the European Court of Human Rights?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nBill Clinton is fairly fluent in which language other than English?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nOf those currently independent, which country was the first to give (and not subsequently revoke) full voting rights country-wide to women?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Which car company, in 1986, comissioned \"\"Cars\"\", a series of artworks to track the evolution of its designs, from Andy Warhol?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat country in North Africa, bordered by Tunisia, Libya, Niger, Mali, Mauritania, Western Sahara, Morocco and the Mediterranean Sea, is the largest country on the Mediterranean, and the second largest on the African continent and in the Arab world?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"What is the \"\"proper name\"\" for the main character in a series of novels by John Updike, who is nicknamed \"\"Rabbit\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn January 2013 Novak Djokovi and Victoria Azarenka won the respective men's and women's titles in which Championship?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn 1993, Eritrea became independent from which country?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe UK TV series, All Ceatures Great and Small, concerned what area of activity?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIodine is added to table salt to prevent what?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nAndy Schleck competes in what sport at an international level?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nOn which coast of South America would you find the country of Venezuela?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the generic title of a series of French comic strips that were written originally by Ren Goscinny and illustrated by Albert Uderzo?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich 1944 musical film, directed by Vincente Minnelli, starred Judy Garland, Mary Astor, Leon Ames, Marjorie Main and Margaret O'Brien who were going to the Louisianna Purchase Exposition of 1904?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nOrnette Coleman, Louis Armstrong and Charles Mingus are associated with what style of music?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich semi-aquatic carnivorous mammal of the weasel family has only two living species: the American and the European?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"What year did Jean-Francois Champollion publish the first correct translation of Egyptian hieroglyphs from the Rosetta Stone, the Roman Catholic Church take Galileo Galilei's \"\"Dialogue\"\" off their list of banned books, and Britain repeal the death penalty for over 100 crimes?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho was the first woman to fly solo from England to Australia?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn the USA in 1912, Theodore Roosevelt formed the Progressive Party when he lost the Republican nomination to William Howard Taft. What was the party also known as?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat cereal crop is used to make single malt whisky in Scotland?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe region of Catalonia is part of which country?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nBetween 1987 and 2006, Ratu Sir Kamisese Mara, Commodore Frank Bainimarama, Mahendra Chaudhry, Laisenia Qarase, Lieutenant Colonel Sitiveni Rabuka, George Speight and Ratu Josefa Iloilo were involved in the politics of which country?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the ninth month of the Muslim year, a period of fasting during which there is strict abstinence during daylight from food, drink and perfume?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Who (although he claims that the author was an entity named Aiwass, his personal Holy Guardian Angel or \"\"Higher Self\"\") is credited with writing \"\"Liber AL vel Legis\"\", the central sacred text of Thelema, commonly referred to as The Book of the Law, in 1904?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Mukhtar Al-Bakri, Sahim Alwan, Faysal Galab, Shafal Mosed, Yaseinn Taher and Yahya Goba were collectively known as the \"\"Lackawanna Six\"\" and by what other name?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Literally, what old French word translates approximately as \"\"white food\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"\"\"Cassata Siciliana\"\" is a type of what?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho was the only Prime Minister of Great Britain born outside the British Isles?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat was the Olympics venue announced by Jacques Rogge as his last before he resigned as President of the IOC?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is a legislative or executive act by which a state restores those who may have been guilty of an offence against it to the positions of innocent people?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nQuadrille, a popular card game in the 18th century, is for four players with a deck of how many?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nOn the buttons of a VCR or DVD player, what does the sign in the shape of a double right pointing arrow mean?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich monastic order, founded in 529 AD, was based at a monastery at Monte Cassino, Italy, until it was sacked in 580, when the monks fled to Rome and then spread throughout Europe?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nKelly Slater is an American professional sportsman in what field?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the name for the process by which heat is transferred by the motion of a fluid?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Up to 1974, the title of \"\"Negus\"\" was used for the traditional rulers of what country?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThomas Lanier Williams III, American playwright, became better known under what name?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the painful and incurable, so far, condition characterised by uterine cells growing outside the uterus?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Who was the subject of the 2007 film \"\"La Vie En Rose\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho, in the years prior to World War II, conceived and oversaw the development of an integrated air defence system for England which included radar, human observers, raid plotting and radio control of aircraft?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nAreas on the Canadian eastern coast share their name with two breeds of dog, Newfoundland and which other?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhere are New Zealand's parliament buildings?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nGeneral Franco, the Spanish military general, was head of state of Spain from October 1936 following the Spanish Civil War, until when?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich Chinese dynasty ruled from the 14th to the 17th century?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe composer Frdric Chopin had a decade-long affair with which French author?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe Sinai Peninsula is part of which country?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the last Grand Slam tennis tournament played in a calendar year?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"What relation was Marlin to Nemo in the film \"\"Finding Nemo\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is a more formal name for ear wax?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe Australian Tennis Open is played in what city?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nSaint Therese is associated with which town?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe game Ticket to Ride involves what kind of transport?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe Mekong River rises in the Tibetan plateau and runs through or between six countries - China, Burma, Thailand, Cambodia, Vietnam and which other?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhere are St. Peter's Basilica and the Sistine Chapel?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat was the name of the Roman road that stretched from Dover, Kent, almost to Shrewsbury, Shropshire, a distance of 322 km (200 miles)?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich red dwarf star, approximately 4.2 light-years distant in the constellation of Centaurus is the nearest star to the Sun?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"What were the last words of Romeo in Shakespeare's \"\"Romeo and Juliet\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"In the sentence \"\"Wherever he went, he carried the scratching cat, his eyes red.\"\", what part of speech is \"\"his eyes red\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat object was unveiled outside John Lennon Airport, Liverpool, in 2005?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe 2009 season of the Indian Premier League, a Twenty20 cricket competition initiated by the Board of Control for Cricket in India, was held where?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhen did the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms, the bill of rights entrenched in Canadian law as part of the Constitution Act, come into force?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn 2008 government in Bhutan was changed from an absolute monarchy to what?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nHe was the fourth of 6 children and the oldest surviving, was a choir singer, a painter, a writer, an admirer of Martin Luther, a decorated soldier and a politician. Who was he?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat, according to Greek legend, was built at Cnossos, Crete, by Daedalus?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat kind of sport is French Ring Sport?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho was the first Englishman to lead an expedition to circumnavigate the earth by sea, and died of dysentery in the West Indies 16 years later?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the name for a rotating rod with oblong lobes sticking out of it, that is fitted in a car's engine block?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat was the maiden name of Billie Jean King before she married Lawrence King in Long Beach, California on 17 September 1965?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is a name for the abstract study of topics such as quantity, structure, space, and change?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich of the actors who portrayed Dr Who, famous from the UK TV series of the same name, appeared almost exclusively on radio, film, written works, and comic strips?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhen were the first Winter Paralympics held?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Which US president was behind \"\"The Indian Removal Act\"\" of 1830, which paved the way for the reluctant and often forcible emigration of tens of thousands of American Indians to the West?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nTravelling up the St Lawrence River from its mouth, which is the first major city on its shores?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIf you travel due south from Detroit, Michigan, what is the first country you reach?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho was expelled from the Surrealist movement due to his views on the Spanish Civil War?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhen is the original version of the statue Mannekin Pis thought to have been built?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhere is the ancient game of senet traditionally played?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho was Queen of France as the wife of Henry II (who reigned for 15 years from 1547) and remained the dominant person in France after his death during the reign of 3 of her 4 sons until 1589?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat country, after having governed it for 155 years, transferred its sovereignty of Hong Kong to China in 1997?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhen the 1992 Maastricht Treaty established the European Union and led to a common currency in Europe, what was the currency called?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhen did the Goa'uld first appear in the US/Canada TV series Stargate SG-1?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho scored the most goals in the 2012/13 English Premier League season?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat would be most useful in playing a game of backgammon?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho, in 1960, made international news for banging his shoe on a table in the UN?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Which German was deprived of his nationality in 1938 mainly for writing \"\"All Quiet On The Western Front\"\" and \"\"The Road Back\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn October 2003, which cricketer, playing in a Test series against Zimbabwe, scored a record 380 not out?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nDancer and actress Josie Marcus was the third wife of whom?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat was invented in the 1940s by Percy Spencer, an American self-taught engineer from Howland, Maine, who was building magnetrons for radar sets?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe name of the city of Firenze in Italy is usually anglicised to what?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe oldest still operating national parliament in Europe governs which country?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Who was King of England when Daniel Defoe published \"\"Robinson Crusoe\"\" and Jonathan Swift published \"\"Gulliver's Travels\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"What is the first line of \"\"Walk on the Wild Side\"\" by Lou Reed, released as a single in 1972?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Under what name are the participants in the UK TV series \"\"QI\"\" currently known?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nAccording to Greek legend, who was the muse of Music?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe London production of which play by acclaimed Australian playwright, David Williamson, won him the George Devine Award, the first time for a non-UK writer?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nCable News Network (CNN), the first channel to provide 24-hour television news coverage, was founded by Ted Turner in what year?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn 2009 Artem Silchenko was first in the Red Bull World Series held at Antalya, Turkey & Sisikon, Switzerland in which sport?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe Himalayas and Tien Shan, or Tian Shan, lie north and south of which other major mountain range?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the name of the scientific discipline that deals with the measurement and representation of the Earth, including its gravitational field, in a three-dimensional time-varying space?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich college was founded by Henry VI in 1440?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn the books by A A Milne, what was Eeyore?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat complex of artificial biological environments near St Blazey and St Austell in Cornwall was opened to the public in 2001?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Judi Dench won an Oscar for Best Supporting Actressfor playing which character in the 1998 film \"\"Shakespeare in Love\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhen did the US TV series, Buffy the Vampire Slayer, begin its six years of seasons?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich pigment is named after an Italian city?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Who released the albums \"\"Sentimental Journey\"\", \"\"Goodnight Vienna\"\", \"\"Bad Boy\"\", \"\"Old Wave\"\" and \"\"Vertical Man\"\" between 1970 and 1999?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"What genre is the TV series \"\"Taggart\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhere would you find the metatarsal bone?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho is the current, in 2014, President of the IOC?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe island of Honsh is part of which country?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is in a human's thoracic cavity?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"In 2011 the Classic Brit Awards named who as \"\"Artist of the Decade\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich figure from Scottish history was played by Mel Gibson in a 1995 film?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe Malagasy people form the main ethnic group of which country?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe December 21, 1988, Pan Am Flight 103 en route from London to New York and at the time over Lockerbie, Scotland, is recorded as having been blown up by whom?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich English civil engineer's most famous project was the construction of Tower Bridge over the River Thames in London?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is kept in the sump of a motor car engine?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nGordon Ramsay opened a restaurant in 2001 in which London hotel?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nHow many military conflicts have been generally given the name of World War?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich US river ends up at the Chesapeake Bay?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is someone allergic to if they have coeliac disease?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich city is generally accepted as the birthplace of Grunge, a subgenre of alternative rock that emerged during the mid-1980s?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is an alternative name for Whit Sunday the time when, according to Christian tradition, the Holy Spirit descended on the Apostles?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nYelena Isinbayeva broke her first World record in 2003 and continued to break records until 2009 in what sport?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhen the Dutch explorer Abel Tasman discovered what is now known as Tasmania, Australia, in his 1642 voyage what did he name it?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nIn what field was the 15th century Flemish Jan van Eyck famous?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nBob Hoskins, an English actor awarded and acclaimed for roles in TV and film ranging from gangsters to playing opposite a cartoon, died in April 2014 at 71; he also, at the age of over 60, played something very close to a romantic interest in which film?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe ship Andrea Gail features in which 1997 book and 2000 film?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe writer Tolstoy fundraised for, and donated the proceeds from some of his writing towards, helping the practitioners of what religious movement?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"What is the birth name of Kim Wilde, the daughter of 1950s UK rock 'n' roller Marty Wilde, whose debut single \"\"Kids in America\"\" (1981) reached #2 in the UK Singles Chart?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho was an R&B; musician from Houston, Texas, raised mostly in Los Angeles, California, who, in addition to his successful Grammy Award-winning career as a solo artist, collaborated with many musicians including The Beatles, The Rolling Stones, The Band, Little Richard, Ray Charles, Eric Clapton, Bob Dylan and Johnny Cash?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Which author famously upset her publisher by beginning a book with \"\"I am quite tired of making goody goody books about nice people\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nHarvey Littleton, Dominick Labino, Dale Chihuly, Dante Marioni, Fritz Driesbach and Marvin Lipofsky are associated with producing art from what material?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich 19th century American poet wrote over 1,000 poems which were published between 1890 and 1945, after her death?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat part of the body produces insulin?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nOne of the largest countries in Africa derived its food wealth for thousands of years from the regular flooding of which river?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe king of what country became Iceland's ruler by treaty in 1262?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhere does the Yellow River have its source?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"In 1976 or 1977, John Carpenter and Debra Hill began drafting a story titled \"\"The Babysitter Murders\"\", which eventually became what film?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nA mill in Woodbridge, Suffolk, England, built in the 12th century, reconstructed in 1792, further restored in 2010 and currently in full working order is a early English example of a mill powered by what?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"\"\"Wuthering Heights\"\" by Emily Bront tells the story of which two lovers?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat name is given to the declaration of aims and policies of a political party before an election?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nEugne Arnold Dolmetsch (1858-1940) is seen as largely responsible for promoting what for use in schools?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Known in the USA as \"\"The March King\"\" he made his first recordings with Columbia Phonograph Company in 1890; what was his name?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the commercial capital of India?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"In which \"\" Star Wars\"\" episode does Anakin Skywalker transform into the black-suited Darth Vader?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nTo prove his theories of the diaspora of South American peoples, who sailed in a balsa raft called Kon Tiki across the Pacific Ocean in 1947?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Complete the title of this James Bond film: \"\"From Russia With ... \"\"\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWho was crowned MotoGP World Champion after he finished third in the Malaysian Grand Prix on 10 October 2010?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat would you expect if you asked for Focaccia in an Italian restaurant?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat country lies to north of the Republic of Chad?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nThe waters of the Gulf of Mexico flow to meet the Atlantic Ocean through what?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Which police station is at the centre of the long-running UK TV series \"\"The Bill\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nA tropical plant that grows several feet high, with a large fleshy root that contains an acrid milk juice, poisonous in its natural form, produces from the juice, extracted under pressure and purified, a staple foodstuff called what?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat shape are honeycomb cells?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"After stints backing Little Richard and the Isley Brothers, who was discovered leading \"\"Jimmy James and the Blue Flames\"\" at the Caf Wha? in New York and taken to London on 26 September 1966 to make hit records?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhich Earl of Essex, after being sent to Ireland as Governor-General in 1599, being briefly imprisoned and leading a rebellion against Queen Eliabeth I, was executed in 1601?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat novel was published by Bob Dylan in 1971?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nDragon boat racing, as part of a complex of ceremonies, is thought to have originated where?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\nWhat is the name of a device, consisting essentially of two wires of different metals, whereby heat energy may be changed to electrical energy?\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"Which Bob Dylan song begins \"\"You got a lotta nerveTo say you are my friend. When I was down, You just stood there grinning\"\"?\"\n\n### Response:\n", "### Instruction:\n\"In Australia, what is known as a \"\"Laughing Jackass\"\"?\